page.title: 01Arkengarthdale and West Moor
page.content: This block consists of high heather moorland to the high point of 668 metres falls in altitute to the north and east. The sheep are the one sign tht man is now using the land. Signs of previous occupation/use are in the disused mining levels in great punchard gill. The other sign of land usage is the sections of heather burn. Game keepers help keep grouse on that section of moor, so that in the open season, sportsmen can shoot the birds from the butts on moor east of Annaside beck. The busiest day of year is the second saturday in June, when approx 250 walkers/runners competing in the swaledale marathon make their way up footpath to great punchard head before heading south for Gunnerside.
